Comment: For a moment lets just look at what we know so far. Congresswoman Wilson, a Democrat from the district the young man grew up in that tragically lost his life, claim:
(1)  she recalls  overhearing Mr Trump more than once say "I am sure he must have known what he signed up for"; 
(2) she admits not hearing the whole phone call;
(3) she has not recalled anything else publicly that she remembers from the phone call;

Subsequently she has gone on to claim this is "Trump's Benghazi" and the phone call a "cover-up" for mismanagement in Niger. 

Trump for his part has denied the recollection and claimed that she is misrepresenting the conversation. 

Sounds like classic politicking; but really in a week with some pretty significant Trump administration developments this is what BS/DM give us?

I think this mostly speaks for itself, especially to jump on this so quickly. The motivation here is confirmation bias and unfortunately why the DM US reporting is so poor and irrelevant.

Comment: Probably the easiest way to reduce congestion is to:
1:  require, and actually enforce, each party to acknowledge up front what is mutually and, by the evidence, obvious;
2: make it a criminal offence for a lawyer (or any officer of the court) to witness any affidavit containing a statement they know to be untrue, and that they physically wrote;
3. Make it a criminal offence for a lawyer to make a statement in Court that has no sound evidentiary basis (ie is contradicted by clear evidence);
4: tell the crown to spend a lot more time prosecuting perjury charges against system players;
5: make the vested players in Self Regulatory Organisations open to civil and criminal action for overt negligence in investigations, procedure development, and conclusions;
6: Make it a criminal offence for a person to refuse to provide a document that is required to be produced by SRO regulation or legislation, or to delay or to cause to be delayed the production of that document.

Then enforce it.

Comment: This dust-up is near to being "internationalized". Obviously what's driving it is agenda (official & other) of the upcoming Synod on the Youth. Whatever the stated summary the synod will be dominated by two "issues": youth and the refugee crisis & LGBTQ concerns. The notion of *journeying/welcoming* uniting the two.

In the running up the growing complexity of this controversy surrounding Fr. Martin is playing its part. The open question, now, is how will Pope Francis sweep into this dust-up to signal this & that?

To show his support for Fr, Martin Pope Francis can:

1) invite Fr. Martin, as an editor of America, for a sit-down interview;
2) con-celebrate with him at a Jesuit sanctuary in Rome;
3) suggest a photo-op receiving Fr, Martin's book, "Bridges";
or - the cake icing -
4) task Fr. Martin to facilitate a working-group to review & revise those pesky "gay paragraphs" in the Catechism. This would set the tone and signal the anticipated end game for the upcoming synod.
